## 2. How we work

### 2.0 Sessions and departments
This project is run by **separate Claude Code sessions by role**, with the committente as the message **bus** (sessions don't talk directly). Enabled departments: **{{DEPARTMENTS}}**.

- **Manager** ({{MANAGER_MODEL}}) — plans Macro→Sub→Micro, decides architecture/product, triages, writes sprints, **and is the only actor that commits/pushes to `main`.** Owns: `CLAUDE.md`, `ActualStatus.md`, the structure of `Sprint.md`, `Sprint_Done.md`, `COMMITTENTE.md`.
- **Execution session** (operative, disposable) — runs the **defined micros** of the current sub-sprint. Each turn it first checks: which sub is current? are its micros defined and at a stop point? → act accordingly.
- **Persistent departments** — each owns only its folder, keeps a `STATUS.md` + `INTERFACE.md`. Mandates & boundaries: see the Bottega `docs/03-roles.md` and each `departments/*.md` recipe.

**Execution session may edit:** ✅ `Sprint.md` — only to check `[x]` micros it executed **and** verified, with a timestamp. ✅ `ActualStatus.md` — factual state. ✅ the deliverable files of the current sub. ❌ everything else is read-only (the manager records decisions).

**Execution session MUST STOP:** at the end of each sub-sprint (deliver "ready to test", don't start the next sub without an explicit GO); when the next sub's micros aren't defined (don't invent them); at GO/NO-GO gates; facing any decision beyond pure execution → **escalate**, don't decide.

### 2.1 Three levels: Macro → Sub → Micro
- **Macro** (`S1`…): big coherent objective. **Sub** (`S1.A`): substantial, independently testable block — the unit the committente validates. **Micro** (`S1.A.1`): largest safe single-pass deliverable.
- Define Sub→Micro **just-in-time** (only the imminent sub). Tag each micro with the recommended model.

### 2.2 Work-orders & escalation
A work-order is a self-contained block in `Sprint.md` (files in scope, ordered micros, invariants, definition-of-done, model per micro). Launch = a pointer (`/lancia-operativa <name>`); rules are **not** re-stated per launch. Escalation = a self-sufficient message (task ref, context, options, where the problem is) → committente → manager.

### 2.3 The INTERFACE protocol (persistent departments)
Each persistent department has an `INTERFACE.md` mailbox (`## 📍 Digest` / `## 📥 From Manager` / `## 📤 From <Dept>`).
- **Department at start:** read `## From Manager`, do open `[ ]` requests.
- **Department at close:** update digest, write `## From <Dept>`, check `[x]`, commit+push its folder.
- **Manager at start of every session and before every gate:** pull & read all digests + open dept items, triage, answer in `## From Manager`, check `[x]`. *This replaces "remind me to check."*

### 2.4 Commit & push
- Work on **`main`** directly. **Only the manager commits/pushes**, after the committente's OK on a validated block, with an **exhaustive** message. No WIP commits, no push without asking.
- No per-session branches by default; if the tool auto-creates one, the manager merges it to `main`. Execution sessions **don't commit** — they leave changes for the manager.
- Departments commit **scoped to their own folder**.

### 2.5 End-of-sprint discipline (manager)
1. `Sprint.md`: check `[x]`, timestamp; move a closed macro to `Sprint_Done.md`. 2. `ActualStatus.md`: done / works / next. 3. `git commit` + `push` (exhaustive). 4. Notify the committente. *(Updating a file ≠ re-reading it.)*

### 2.6 Switching sprints / compacting
It's normal to finish several sprints per session. Don't re-read the `.md` files mid-session. When a heavy next sprint begins, the manager **reminds** the committente that `/compact` or a fresh session keeps context efficient (`/compact` is typed by the human).

### 2.7 Agentic automation governance
Before building/granting autonomy to any automation, apply the Bottega `docs/06-agentic-governance.md` checklist. Project-specific automation decisions live in `AUTOMATION_PLAYBOOK.md` (root), maintained by the manager.

### 2.8 Lightweight conventions (token-aware)
Cheap conventions that prevent expensive waste. They add a handful of lines here (read on demand) and files read **on demand** — never new auto-loaded files.
- **Gate states:** PASS · CONCERNS (ship with a noted caveat) · FAIL · WAIVED (a risk consciously accepted). One line in the relevant `STATUS.md`/`ActualStatus.md` — no per-gate files.
- **Remediation cap:** after **2 failed fix attempts** on the same issue, stop and escalate to the committente. No infinite loops.
- **Planning tiers:** trivial → just do it · standard → a work-order · epic → a brief, then **shard** into self-contained stories (each with its own acceptance criteria + tests).
- **Decision log:** record each real decision as ONE appended line in `DECISIONS.md` (read on demand). Never re-litigate a logged decision — supersede it explicitly.
- **Handover:** before `/compact` or closing, run `/handover` — it refreshes `ActualStatus.md`'s 📌 STATE as a clean resume point. Keep it short; point to `Sprint.md`/`DECISIONS.md` rather than copying them.
- **Committente action-items ("ball in your court"):** the manager keeps a short list in `ActualStatus.md` of decisions/tasks only the committente can do, each with **what it blocks**. At **every session start** and in `/handover`, surface the open items — remind the committente unprompted. On resolution, log it to `DECISIONS.md` and prune the item.
- **Operative handoff is from disk, not narration:** a finished operative writes its **Execution Record into its work-order block in `Sprint.md`**. When the committente says an operative finished, the manager triages **from disk** — reads that record + `git diff`/`git status`, runs the relevant tests — it does **not** ask the committente to describe the work. The committente only points to *which* work-order finished.
- **Every department triages from disk; the channel is a convenience:** a persistent department's source of truth is its `STATUS.md` + artifacts, not its `INTERFACE.md` (which mainly carries the department's *questions*). The manager reads `STATUS.md`/artifacts at start; if a department forgot to update its `INTERFACE.md`, the manager **reconciles the digest from disk and proceeds — never blocks**. Authoring a department's outbound message stays the *department's* job; the manager only self-heals.
- **Work-orders are territory-scoped:** every work-order has **one owner** — a single department's folder, or the shared root (`.github/`, build config, etc.). All its files in scope must fall under that one territory; work spanning two territories is **split** into separate, owner-tagged work-orders. **Code that lives in a department's folder is that department's**: the execution lane may *implement* it, but scoped to that folder and on the owner's behalf, and the owning department is kept in the loop (its `INTERFACE.md`). Before launching an operative, the manager checks the scoped files share one owner — if not, it splits.
- **Session type matches task type (routing):** a department session (`/lancia-<dept>`) does that department's **recurring domain work** (publish, validate, …). **Building its tooling/code is an EXECUTION task** → launch `/lancia-operativa` with a work-order owner-tagged to that department's folder. **Never launch a department session to write its own code** (its charter is domain-mode, not build-mode).
- **Launch invariant — work-order in the read-path:** don't tell the committente to launch a session until a **self-contained, actionable `[ ]` work-order** sits where that session actually reads it — `Sprint.md` for an execution session, `INTERFACE.md → From Manager` for a department. Self-contained = scope + acceptance criteria + **blocking decisions already resolved** + an explicit list of **what is NOT a blocker**. Launching with nothing actionable in the read-path is an anti-pattern.
- **Deliver the launch command, not a description:** the green-light hands the committente the **literal, copy-pasteable launch line with all arguments filled** (e.g. `/lancia-operativa <exact work-order name>`), never a prose pointer — the committente is *transport*, they shouldn't reconstruct or retype the target. A prose pointer + a bare command = no `$ARGUMENTS` = the session stops to ask. (Keep the command's *ask-if-ambiguous* safety net: fix by passing the argument, never by making the session guess.)
- **Session isolation — non-org sessions get their own worktree:** the ORG owns the **main working dir on `main`** and is the only one that writes to `main`. Every other session (operative, research, a department writing code) works in a **dedicated git worktree on its own branch** and commits there — it must **never `git checkout -b` or commit in the shared main dir** (switching the shared HEAD collides with the org: commits land on the wrong branch, detached HEAD). Pattern the launch commands follow: `git worktree add .claude/worktrees/<label> -b <branch>`, work + commit there; the ORG reviews (`git diff main..<branch>` + the Execution Record) and merges; then `git worktree remove`. This **composes** with the rooting rule: you *launch* from the repo (so slash commands resolve), then *isolate* into your worktree before writing. **Guard:** if you're not the ORG and you're in the main repo dir on `main`, stop and isolate first. **Test/build deps stay in the work-order's territory** — declare them in the in-scope folder's own package; never `add` them into a neighbouring project (an operative scoped to `content/publishing/` doesn't touch `engine/`'s deps).

